@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{you ni}}" grammar="@HI{{you ni}}"}}

<body>

<h1>@HI{{you ni}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vru{{}}(<em>non-volitional</em>) @EM{{@HI{{you ni}}}}, <em>volitional expression</em>
<li> @Vnai{{}} @EM{{@HI{{you ni}}}}, <em>volitional expression</em>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
These sentence patterns indicate a purpose.
</p>

<p>
The verb before @EM{{@HI{{you ni}}}} should be a non-volitional one or a verb in the negative form.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{quick}}ku @KJ{{swim}}geru@EM{{you ni}}, @KJ{{every^day^practice^learn}}shite imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I practice every day so that I can swim quickly.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{forget}}renai@EM{{you ni}},@KT{{memo}}shite kudasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Please take a memo so you will not forget.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

The similar expression <a href="grammar-tame-ni.html">@HI{{tame ni}}</a> is used in clauses with verbs
that contain volition,
whereas @EM{{@HI{{you ni}}}} is used with verbs that do not. Note that if the verb involved
is @HI{{naru}}, then whether or not volition is invovled depends on the sentence.
</br>

